    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-07-30T14:29:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-07-30T14:29:00-05:00" n="590"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d590">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 861.00/2397</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Russia</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_FDR1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Francis</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Murmansk</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-07-31T00:00:00+04:31">
                            <hi rend="italic">July 31, 1918, midnight</hi>
                        </date>. <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received August 1, 4.07
                        p.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>342. Just arrived Murman with Italian Ambassador, <persName corresp="#p_LFO1"
                        >Lindley</persName> and French Chargé d’Affaires. Other chiefs awaiting
                    advices, Kandalaksha. <persName corresp="#p_PMGFC1">Poole</persName>
                    <note n="2" xml:id="d590fn2">
                        <persName corresp="#p_PMGFC1">Maj. Gen. Frederick C. Poole</persName>, in
                        command of British forces in north Russia.</note> and
                        <persName>Kemp</persName>
                    <note n="3" xml:id="d590fn3">Rear Admiral <persName>Thomas W. Kemp</persName>,
                        R. N.</note> left for Archangel this morning taking Bierer<note n="4"
                        xml:id="d590fn4">Capt. <persName>Bion B. Bierer</persName>. commanding the
                        U. S. S. <hi rend="italic">Olympia.</hi>
                    </note> and <persName corresp="#p_MLHS1">Martin</persName> and about 1,000
                    British, French soldiery including 50 American sailors. Anti-Bolshevik
                    revolution planned there for to-day and if successful as anticipated then Allied
                    forces will land Archangel without opposition August 2.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_FDR1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Francis</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
